Alice Davis supervised the creation of more than 150 highly detailed costumes for It's a Small World Animatronics, and even created standards still used by Imaginary today. Marianne Meng became the first woman promoted to manager. She always gave something back to the community. Eventually helping create the Disney Volunteers Program, Cicely Rigdon tried five times to get hired. Starting off as a ticket seller, Cicely moved on up to supervisor of guest relations, eventually leading and developing the Ambassador Program. Thank you for helping pave the way for us women at Disney.

transcribe_text: How I made the giant squish. First I filmed myself as a tiny little guy waving at the big guy. Then I filmed myself as the big guy waving from behind the mountain. To do this, I just stood closer to the camera. I paused at the moment of the jump. I took a still image of the empty scene and I cut out the sky using Photoshop's object selection tool. I exported the PNG and dropped that on top of the giant. I dropped the little guy on top of it all and put a mask around him. Pro tip, if you right click on a clip, you can rename it so you don't get confused. When I was filming, I set up a green screen so I could jump in and out of the frame. I used ultra key to remove the green. I increased the size of the foot and moved it to be covering the little guy. To sell the effect more, I also laid out my shoes and shirt and added them using a still image of this cut out. I took a freeze frame of me waving and added the basic 3D effect, which allowed me to turn little me to look flat. I reduced the opacity. To make the floating away effect, I nested the elements, animated the motion, added and animated a turbulent displace effect, as well as added a directional blur. I used the Lumetri color for color correction. And now, voila! Masterpiece!

I was able to sing in the Voices of Liberty Candlelight Processional cast and I've been here ever since. We like to say in Voices of Liberty that you listen harder than you sing. transcribe_text: The effect that I'm working on today is 3D animation. In After Effects, the first thing I'm gonna do is duplicate my footage layer. Then using the roto tool, I'm gonna outline the body of the dancer, and then just go back and clean up frame by frame. So now that we've got our dancer isolated from the background, we're gonna start to animate. In Window, make sure that your track panel is open, and then we're gonna take the track camera and apply that to our base footage. Between any three of these points it creates, I'm gonna click to add solid and camera. So now as the camera moves, the shape tracks with it. I'm gonna right click the solid, pre-compose, and then double click inside the layer to delete the automatic shape and replace it with the image that I wanna animate. Then I'll just play around with the size, dimensions, and position till it's where I want it to be. Now to get the shape to go behind the dancer, I'm gonna move that layer below the body layer. If you wanna customize the movement of the shape beyond just the tracking, you can also scrub to where you want the shape to be at a specific point, keyframe it, scrub to where you want it to end, and then adjust the position. Repeat that for the rest of your shapes, and you're done.
